Es + wenn. Two analyses are possible: 1. Acc/Dat-EXP V ("es" is treated as expletive), 2. X-STM V Y-EXP + ambiguous. The first one seems more natural to me while the second leads to a different reading, which is also possible (especially when "es" is stressed). (A third analysis, in which "es" is treated as expletive and corresponding to the wenn-clause, which would be the subject then, cannot be maintained because in contrast to a dass-clause the wenn-clause, that seems to express the stimulus here,  cannot be used without "es". This shows that it is not the subject. Maybe one could say that "es" is a nonexpletive pronoun coreferent with the wenn-clause)
